<section class="home-section">
  <div class="prose">
    <h2>Voice and tone</h2>
    <p>
      Write as a small group of practitioners, not an organization with a communications department.
      CoCitizen is enthusiastic about tools it didn't build, transparent about what it is and isn't,
      and slightly tongue-in-cheek about the fact that some of this work happens in genuinely difficult
      places. Been there, done that, unfazed and still chipper.
    </p>
    <p>
      Avoid mission-statement cadence, startup-speak, and NGO formality. Prefer specific and concrete
      over broad and impressive. When in doubt, be more honest than polished. The reader is a peer —
      someone evaluating whether these tools are real and whether the people behind them know what
      they're doing.
    </p>
    <p class="muted"><strong>Sounds like us:</strong> "Some of these have been... challenging situations."</p>
    <p class="muted"><strong>Doesn't sound like us:</strong> "CoCitizen is committed to empowering civil society through innovative open-source solutions."</p>
  </div>
</section>

